hands_on_practices.problem:
An isotropic solution of a chiral organic compound is analyzed by Vibrational Circular Dichroism (VCD) and Infrared (IR) absorption spectroscopy at the wavenumber $	ilde{
u}_{0} = 1715\,	ext{cm}^{-1}$ corresponding to a well-isolated carbonyl stretching mode. The optical pathlength is $0.0100\,	ext{cm}$ and the solute concentration is $0.0500\,	ext{mol}\,	ext{L}^{-1}$. After baseline correction, the measured IR absorbance at $	ilde{
u}_{0}$ is $A(	ilde{
u}_{0}) = 0.820$, and the measured circular differential absorbance is $\Delta A(	ilde{
u}_{0}) = +2.050 	imes 10^{-3}$. Using only fundamental definitions of absorbance, differential absorbance, and the dissymmetry factor, compute the dissymmetry factor at this wavenumber. Then, interpret the magnitude and sign of your result in terms of the underlying rotational strength for this vibrational transition, starting from the Beer–Lambert law and the definition of rotational strength as the imaginary part of the electric–magnetic dipole transition moment scalar product. Report the numerical value of the dissymmetry factor rounded to four significant figures as a pure number without units.
